name: ethyl 3,4-dimethoxybenzoate
Reason: To predict the melting point of ethyl 3,4-dimethoxybenzoate, we consider the impacts of the functional groups and structural features in comparison with a similar basic structure. The basic structure to which we compare is benzoic acid, which has a melting point of 122 °C. This serves as our reference point. The ethyl ester group (-COOEt) generally decreases the melting point because it reduces the ability for hydrogen bonding compared to the carboxylic acid (-COOH) group; this can be intuitively estimated to lower the melting point by around -60 to -80 °C. Additionally, the two methoxy groups (-OCH3) present on the aromatic ring would further reduce the melting point since they introduce electron-donating effects that destabilize crystal packing and thus lower melting point; each -OCH3 group can be estimated to reduce the melting point by about -10 to -15 °C. Adding up the effects of the functional groups, we can approximate the reduction in melting point due to the functional group modifications.
Prediction: The predicted melting point would be the melting point of benzoic acid (122 °C) minus the effect of the ethyl ester group (-70 °C as an average estimate) and the two methoxy groups (2 times -12.5 °C, the average estimate), which amounts to 122 - 70 - (2 * 12.5) = 122 - 70 - 25 = 27 °C.
